GetMeThere1 3 days ago
Having a very general impression of organic chemistry (carbon backbones, reactive groups, a few more things) is fine. Otherwise, ONLY ORGANIC CHEMISTS need to know organic chemistry. I went to med school and I have a PhD in cell biology. I never needed any organic chemistry for ANY of that (despite EVERYONE insisting it is vital). Anyone who says different is a LIAR! Furthermore, if you consider carefully and without bias, you will see that this brief lecture is actually DEVOID of any useful or meaningful information (for anyone who has enough basic chemistry to understand what atoms and molecules are, and enough biology to have some idea about what cells do, and how their processes are mediated through macromolecules made up of the well known building blocks of all biological materials). Yeah, epinephrine has a structure (which doesn't MATTER -- as long as you understand the general principle that all enzymes and other binding sites in biology rest on structures fitting together electro-mechanically) -- so what? It matters to anyone synthesizing epinephrine (organic chemists), and it matters to someone working on the biochemistry of epinephrine (i.e., organic chemists who work on biological systems).﻿
